]]<ref name=\"league cup\"/>\n\n'''Derry City'''\n*[[League of Ireland Cup]] winner (1):  [[2018 League of Ireland Cup|2018]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{Soccerway|113425}}\n\n{{Queen of the South F.C. squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Low, Nicky}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Scottish footballers]]\n[[Category:Scottish Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Football League players]]\n[[Category:Scottish Professional Football League players]]\n[[Category:Aberdeen F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Forfar Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Alloa Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Scotland youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Dundee F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Derry City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:League of Ireland players]]\n[[Category:Queen of the South F.C. players]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Nicky Law (disambiguation){{!}}Nicky Law}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name                = Nicky Low\n| fullname            = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1992|01|06|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = [[Greenock]], Scotland\n| height              = \n| position            = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub         = [[East Stirlingshire F.C.|East Stirlingshire]]\n| clubnumber          = \n| youthyears1         = \n| youthclubs1         = [[Aberdeen F.C. Under-20s and Academy|Aberdeen]]\n| years1              = 2010\u20132015 | clubs1 = [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]                        | caps1 = 28 | goals1 = 3\n| years2              = 2011\u20132012 | clubs2 = \u2192 [[Forfar Athletic F.C.|Forfar Athletic]] (loan) | caps2 = 29 | goals2 = 6\n| years3              = 2012\u20132013 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]] (loan)   | caps3 = 10 | goals3 = 0\n| years4              = 2015\u20132018 | clubs4 = [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]]                            | caps4 = 23 | goals4 = 1\n| years5              = 2017\u20132018 | clubs5 = [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]]                    | caps5 = 50 | goals5 = 3 \n| years6              = 2019      | clubs6 = [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]]    | caps6 = 7  | goals6 = 0 \n| years7              = 2019\u2013     | clubs7 = [[East Stirlingshire F.C.|East Stirlingshire]]    | caps7 = 25 | goals7 = 14\n| nationalyears1      = 2009\n| nationalteam1       = [[Scotland national under-17 football team|Scotland U17]]\n| nationalcaps1       = 4\n| nationalgoals1      = 0\n| club-update         = 18:00, 18 May 2019 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n\n'''Nicky Low''' (born 6 January 1992) is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] [[association football|footballer]], who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[East Stirlingshire F.C.|East Stirlingshire]]. Low has previously played for [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]], [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]], [[Forfar Athletic F.C.|Forfar Athletic]], [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]], [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]] and [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]].<ref name=qosprof/>\n\n==Club career==\n===Aberdeen===\nOn 27 January 2010, Low debuted for the ''Dons'' versus [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]], appearing as a substitute. Aberdeen won the match 3\u20130.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_prem/8480378.stm | title=Hearts v Aberdeen | accessdate=7 May 2011 | work=BBC News | date=26 January 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 August 2011, Low was sent out on loan to [[Forfar Athletic F.C.|Forfar Athletic]] until 1 January 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nicky Low and Joe Shaughnessy |url=http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20110830/nicky-low-and-joe-shaughnessy_2212158_2436441 |work=afc.co.uk |publisher=[[Aberdeen F.C.]] |date=30 August 2011 |accessdate=30 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222030816/http://www.afc.co.uk/articles/20110830/nicky-low-and-joe-shaughnessy_2212158_2436441 |archivedate=22 February 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> After impressing on loan, Low returned to the ''Loons'' until the end of the [[2011\u201312 in Scottish football|2011-12]] season. During his time at [[Station Park, Forfar|Station Park]], Low was voted Supporter's Player of the Year and Young Sky Blues Player of the Year.<ref name=qosprof/><ref>{{cite news|title=End of Season Awards|url=http://www.forfarathletic.co.uk/index.php?option=com_flexicontent&view=items&cid=7:latest-news&id=623:end-of-season-awards&Itemid=27 |work=forfarathletic.co.uk| publisher=[[Forfar Athletic F.C.]] |date=30 April 2012 |accessdate=29 August 2013 }}</ref> On 18 October 2012, Low signed for [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]], on loan initially for one month.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wasps capture Low|url=http://www.alloaathletic.co.uk/BlogView.aspx?pageid=2&ItemID=772&mid=2 |work=alloaathletic.co.uk |publisher=[[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]] |date=18 August 2013 |accessdate=29 August 2013 }}</ref> Low's loan spell was then extended until 1 January 2014 before returning to [[Pittodrie Stadium|Pittrodrie]].\n\nOn 29 December 2013, Low scored his first goal for the ''Dons'' in a 1\u20130 victory versus [[Ross County F.C.|Ross County]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Aberdeen 1-0 Ross County|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/25482615|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 December 2013|accessdate=3 January 2014}}</ref> On 16 March in the [[2014 Scottish League Cup Final]] versus [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]], Low appeared as a 70th minute substitute, scoring a spot kick in the penalty shoot-out victory for Aberdeen.<ref name=qosprof/><ref name=\"league cup\">{{cite web|title=Scottish League Cup Final Report|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26502621|publisher=BBC Sport|date=16 March 2014|accessdate=26 December 2014}}</ref> On 15 May 2014, Low signed a new one-year contract with the ''Dons''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Aberdeen trio sign new contracts while Magennis and Vernon depart|url=http://sport.stv.tv/football/clubs/aberdeen/275368-aberdeen-trio-sign-new-contracts-while-magennis-and-vernon-depart/|publisher=STV Sport|date=15 May 2014|accessdate=23 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Dundee===\nOn 20 April 2015, Low signed a pre-contract to sign for [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]] on a three-year deal from the start of the [[2015\u201316 in Scottish football|2015-16]] season.<ref>{{cite web|title=NICKY LOW SIGNS PRE-CONTRACT|url=http://www.dundeefc.co.uk/news/nicky-low-signs-pre-contract|publisher=Dundee F.C.|date=20 April 2015|accessdate=20 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32387184 |title=Aberdeen midfielder Nicky Low signs pre-contract with Dundee |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=20 April 2015 |accessdate=21 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Derry City===\nIn January 2017, Low was sent out on loan to Northern Irish club [[Derry City F.C.|Derry City]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38801313 |title=Derry City sign Dundee midfielder Nicky Low in loan deal |work=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date=30 January 2017 |accessdate=30 January 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, Low's loan spell was extended until 7 November 2017,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.derryjournal.com/sport/football/derry-city/derry-city-nicky-low-has-unfinished-business-at-derry-city-1-8026796 |title=Derry City: Nicky Low has 'unfinished business' at Derry City |first=Simon |last=Collins |work=Derry Journal |publisher=Johnston Publishing Ltd |date=26 June 2017 |accessdate=19 January 2018}}</ref> before returning to [[Dens Park]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eveningtelegraph.co.uk/fp/neil-mccann-show-four-dundee-players-dens-park-exit-door/ |title=Neil McCann could show four Dundee players the Dens Park exit door |first=George |last=Cran |work=Evening Telegraph |publisher=DC Thomson Co Ltd |date=6 January 2018 |accessdate=19 January 2018}}</ref> On 31 January 2018, Low returned to the ''Candystripes'' after winning the previous season's Player of the Year and Players' Player of the Year awards.<ref name=qosprof/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/news/completed-transfers-deadline-day-january-2018/?rid=13929 |title=Completed Transfers - Deadline Day January 2018 |work= |publisher=Scottish FA |date=31 January 2018 |accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref> In May 2018, Low was released by Dundee <ref>{{cite web |url=https://dundeefc.co.uk/news/player-update/ |title=Player update |work= |publisher=Dundee FC |date=16 May 2018 |accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref> and then signed for the ''Candystripes'' on a permanent deal.\n\nLow played in 56 matches for the ''Candystripes'', scoring three goals.<ref>https://www.derryjournal.com/sport/football/derry-city/i-leave-derry-city-with-a-very-heavy-heart-nicky-low-1-8682977</ref>\n\n===Queen of the South===\nOn 27 December 2018, Low agreed to sign for [[Dumfries]] club [[Queen of the South F.C.|Queen of the South]] when the transfer window opened on 1 January 2019,<ref name=qosprof>[http://qosfc.com/news-4275 \"Nicky Low profile\" qosfc.com 5 January 2018]</ref> with his contract scheduled to run until the end of the [[2018-19 in Scottish football|2018-19]] season.<ref>http://www.qosfc.com/news-4262</ref>\n\n===East Stirlingshire===\nOn 14 May 2019, Low signed a pre-contract to join [[East Stirlingshire F.C.|East Stirlingshire]] in the [[Lowland Football League|Lowland League]] for the [[2019-20 in Scottish football|2019-20]] season.<ref>https://www.eaststirlingshirefc.co.uk/archives/4870</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{Updated|19 May 2019}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|